    <h2 id="overview">What Is Sea Moss and Why Is It Trending?</h2>

    <p>Sea moss (Chondrus crispus), also known as Irish moss, is a species of red algae that grows along the rocky Atlantic coastlines of Ireland, Britain, Europe, and North America. It has been consumed as a food and medicine for centuries — Irish families used it during the Great Famine of the 1840s as a calorie source and nutrient supplement, while Caribbean communities have traditionally consumed sea moss beverages for energy, immunity, and sexual health.</p>

    <p>The modern sea moss surge began in the early 2020s, driven by social media influencers, wellness podcasts, and the broader trend toward mineral-dense whole foods. What separates sea moss from the typical supplement trend is its genuinely remarkable mineral profile: laboratory analysis confirms that Chondrus crispus contains 92 of the 102 minerals found in the human body, making it one of the most mineral-dense natural foods on Earth.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">92</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of the 102 minerals found in the human body are present in <strong>sea moss</strong>, including iodine, calcium, potassium, magnesium, sulfur, zinc, iron, manganese, selenium, and phosphorus. This extraordinary mineral density comes from seaweed's unique ability to absorb and bioconcentrate dissolved minerals from ocean water over its growth cycle.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Thyroid & Metabolism</strong>
        <p>Sea moss is one of the richest natural sources of iodine, which the thyroid gland requires to produce T3 and T4 hormones that regulate metabolism, body temperature, and energy production. Iodine deficiency affects approximately 2 billion people globally and is the most common cause of preventable thyroid dysfunction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Immunity & Inflammation</strong>
        <p>Sea moss provides vitamin C, zinc, and selenium — three nutrients essential for immune cell function. Its sulfated polysaccharides have demonstrated anti-inflammatory and antiviral properties in laboratory studies. Traditional Caribbean use for cold and flu recovery has centuries of anecdotal support.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="sparkle" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Skin Health & Hydration</strong>
        <p>The carrageenan in sea moss forms a moisture-retaining film that hydrates skin both topically and when consumed orally. Sea moss also provides sulfur (for collagen crosslinking), vitamin A (for cell turnover), and zinc (for wound healing). Caribbean women have used sea moss gel as a face mask for generations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Digestive Health</strong>
        <p>Sea moss acts as a prebiotic fiber, feeding beneficial gut bacteria. Its mucilaginous (gel-like) quality soothes the digestive tract lining, and carrageenan has been studied for potential gastroprotective effects. The fiber content may also support regular bowel movements and appetite control.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Heart & Blood Health</strong>
        <p>Sea moss provides potassium (which supports blood pressure regulation), omega-3 fatty acids (which reduce inflammation), and fiber (which may lower cholesterol). A 2015 study in BMC Complementary Medicine found that seaweed consumption was associated with reduced cardiovascular risk markers in populations with high seaweed intake.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="fitness" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Energy & Recovery</strong>
        <p>The iron and B-vitamin content in sea moss supports oxygen transport and energy metabolism. Iron deficiency (affecting 10% of American women) directly causes fatigue and reduced exercise performance. Sea moss also provides taurine and amino acids that support muscle recovery and electrolyte balance.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2021 comprehensive review published in <em>Marine Drugs</em> analyzed the bioactive compounds in Chondrus crispus and confirmed that sea moss contains significant quantities of <strong>sulfated polysaccharides, minerals (particularly iodine, potassium, and calcium), antioxidant compounds, and prebiotic fibers</strong> that have demonstrated immunomodulatory, anti-inflammatory, and prebiotic activities in vitro and in animal models. The review called for more human clinical trials to quantify dose-response relationships.</p>
      <cite>Marine Drugs, 2021 — Comprehensive review of Chondrus crispus bioactives</cite>
    </div>

    <!-- EVIDENCE LEVELS -->
    <h2 id="evidence">Benefit-by-Benefit Evidence Assessment</h2>

    <p>Not all sea moss benefits have equal scientific support. Here is our honest assessment of the evidence level for each claimed benefit, rated from strong to emerging based on the quality and quantity of published research.</p>

    <div class="vs-strip">
      <div class="vs-item vs-best">
        <span class="vs-item-label">Strong Evidence</span>
        <h3>Thyroid Support (Iodine)</h3>
