    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Sea Moss Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the benefits of sea moss gummies?</summary>
      <p>Sea moss contains 92 minerals including iodine (thyroid support), zinc and vitamin C (immunity), sulfated polysaccharides (skin hydration), and prebiotic fiber (digestion). Thyroid support is the strongest evidence-backed benefit due to natural iodine content. Other benefits are supported by the mineral profile but have less direct clinical study.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does sea moss really contain 92 minerals?</summary>
      <p>Yes, laboratory analysis confirms Chondrus crispus contains 92 of 102 minerals found in the human body. However, many are present in trace amounts rather than therapeutic doses. The mineral content also varies by harvesting location and processing method.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How does sea moss support thyroid health?</summary>
      <p>Sea moss is one of the richest natural iodine sources. The thyroid requires iodine to produce T3 and T4 hormones that regulate metabolism. Iodine deficiency causes hypothyroidism. However, excessive iodine can also cause thyroid dysfunction — consult your physician if you have thyroid conditions.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is sea moss good for skin?</summary>
      <p>Sea moss contains sulfated polysaccharides that hydrate skin, plus vitamins A, E, K, sulfur, and zinc that support skin health. Caribbean women have used sea moss topically for generations. Oral supplementation may support skin from the inside via its mineral and collagen-supporting nutrient content.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much sea moss should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>Most gummies provide 1000-3000mg per serving. Start with the manufacturer's recommended dose. The primary dosing concern is iodine — the UL is 1100mcg daily. Do not exceed recommended servings, especially with products containing both sea moss and bladderwrack.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can sea moss help with weight loss?</summary>
      <p>Sea moss may modestly support weight management through thyroid support (iodine for metabolic rate) and satiety (gel-forming fibers). Lab studies show seaweed alginates reduce fat absorption. However, no RCTs have tested sea moss gummies specifically for weight loss. Effects are complementary to diet and exercise.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is sea moss safe to take every day?</summary>
      <p>Generally safe at recommended doses. The primary concern is iodine content — excessive iodine can cause thyroid dysfunction. Choose third-party tested products to avoid heavy metal contamination. Consult your physician if you have thyroid conditions, are pregnant, or take thyroid medications.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between Irish sea moss and other seaweeds?</summary>
      <p>Irish sea moss (Chondrus crispus) is a red algae uniquely prized for its 92-mineral density and carrageenan content. Kelp is a brown algae higher in iodine. Spirulina is blue-green algae higher in protein. Chlorella is green algae higher in chlorophyll. Each has a different nutritional profile and health application.</p>
    </details>

